<section xml:id="Graphs_of_the_Sine_and_Cosine_Functions">
  <title>Graphs of the Sine and Cosine Functions</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      The seasons on Earth are caused by axial tilt.
      To visual axial tilt,
      image a pole through the center of Earth and extending through the North and South Pole with Earth spinning around this pole.
      Each spin is one day.
      As the Earth revolves around the sun,
      the North Pole tilts towards the sun and sometimes the South Pole tilts towards the sun,
      this tilting is call <em>axial tilt</em>.
          <idx><h>Axial Tilt</h></idx>
      When the North Pole is closer to the Sun
      (the South Pole is away from the Sun),
      the Northern Hemisphere experiences summer
      (the Southern Hemisphere experiences winter).
      When the axial tilt is reversed and the North Pole is further from the Sun (South Pole is close to the Sun),
      the seasons are reversed.
    </p>
    <p>
      Every day as the Earth spins on its axis,
      the Sun rises from the eastern horizon.
      However, only twice a year will the sun rise due east,
      in the house Hikina.
      One occurrence is during the spring equinox.
      In the northern hemisphere, as spring turns into summer,
      the position the sun rises from will slowly move north,
      until the summer solstice,
      when the sun will rise from the most northern point
      (<m>23.44^{\circ}</m> or the house `\=Aina Ko`olau).
      After this, the position of the rising sun will move south until the fall equinox where the sun will once again rise from due east or Hikina,
      before continuing its southern movement until the winter solstice when the sun will rise from its southern most position
      (<m>-23.44^{\circ}</m> or the house `\=Aina Malanai).
      As winter turns to spring,
      the sun rise will start to move north until the next spring equinox where the position of the sun rise will once again be due east (Hikina).
      This process takes one year before it repeats itself year after year.
      This pattern of the position of the sun rise is a periodic function.
    </p>
    <p>
      The sun's <em>declination</em>
          <idx><h>Declination</h></idx>
      is the angle between the equator and a line from the center of Earth to the sun.
    </p>
    <p>
      June 20 December 21 March 20 September 22
    </p>
    <p>
      In <xref ref="Trigonometry">Chapter</xref>
      we learned about the six trigonometric functions.
      In this section we will study the graphs of the sine and cosine functions to help us understand their use in modeling physical phenomena.
      We will study the graphs of the remaining trigonometric functions in <xref ref="Graphs_of_Other_Trigonometric_Functions">Section</xref>.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>Periodic Functions</title>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
              <idx><h>Period Functions</h></idx>
          A function <m>f</m> is called <term>periodic</term> if there exists a positive number <m>p</m> such that
          <me>
            f(\theta+p)=f(\theta)
          </me>
          for every <m>\theta</m>.
          The smallest number <m>p</m> is called the
          <term>period</term> of <m>f</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      \begin{mybox}[Periodic Properties]
          <idx><h>Period Functions</h></idx>
      <md>
        <mrow>\sin(\theta+2\pi)\amp =\sin\theta \amp  \cos(\theta+2\pi)\amp =\cos\theta \amp  \tan(\theta+\pi)\amp =\tan\theta</mrow>
        <mrow>\csc(\theta+2\pi)\amp =\csc\theta \amp  \sec(\theta+2\pi)\amp =\sec\theta \amp  \cot(\theta+\pi)\amp =\cot\theta</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      \end{mybox}
    </p>
    <p>
      Recall that if <m>\theta</m> is an angle with radian measure <m>t</m>,
      then the <em>six trigonometric functions</em> become
      <md>
        <mrow>\sin \theta\amp =y \amp  \cos \theta\amp =x \amp  \tan \theta\amp =\frac{y}{x}  (x\neq0)</mrow>
        <mrow>\csc \theta\amp =\frac{1}{y}  (y\neq0) \amp  \sec \theta\amp =\frac{1}{x}  (x\neq0) \amp  \cot \theta\amp =\frac{x}{y}  (y\neq0)</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <image>
<latex-image>
